04108nam a22006615i 9780292766631DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212015txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014026812  a97802927666317 a10.7560/7666242doi  a(DE-B1597)587992  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aRA418.3.B6bJ47 2015 4aRA418.3.B6 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a362.109812231 aJerome, Jessica Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Right to Health :bMedicine, Marginality, and Health Care Reform in Northeastern Brazil /cJessica Scott Jerome. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Pirambu: Historical and Contemporary Accounts of Citizenship in a Favela -- t2. A History of Welfare and the Poor in Ceará -- t3. Democratizing Health Care: Health Councils in Pirambu -- t4. Prescribing Knowledge: Farmácia Viva and the Rationalization of Traditional Medicine -- t5. Favors, Rights, and the Management of Illness -- t6. Public and Private Medical Care for a New Generation in Pirambu -- tConclusion: A Politics of Health -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1988, a new health care system, the Sistema Único de Saúde (Unified Health Care System or SUS) was formally established in Brazil. The system was intended, among other goals, to provide universal access to health care services and to redefine health as a citizen’s right and a duty of the state. A Right to Health explores how these goals have unfolded within an urban peripheral community located on the edges of the northeastern city of Fortaleza. Focusing on the decade 1998–2008 and the impact of health care reforms on one low-income neighborhood, Jessica Jerome documents the tensions that arose between the ideals of the reforms and their entanglement with pervasive socioeconomic inequality, neoliberal economic policy, and generational tension with the community. Using ethnographic and historical research, the book traces the history of political activism in the community, showing that, since the community’s formation in the early 1930s, residents have consistently fought for health care services. In so doing, Jerome develops a multilayered portrait of urban peripheral life and suggests that the notion of health care as a right of each citizen plays a major role not only in the way in which health care is allocated, but, perhaps more importantly, in how health care is understood and experienced.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aHealth care reformzBrazilxHistory. 0aMedical carezBrazil. 0aMedical policyzBrazilxHistory. 0aSocial medicinezBrazil. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292766631423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292766631/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK